			<title>Next Citylife game to be an MMO</title>
			<link>http://www.graffe.com/forums/showthread.php?t=59887&amp;goto=newpost</link>
			<pubDate>Tue, 19 Aug 2008 07:52:30 GMT</pubDate>
			<description><![CDATA[Preview: Be a Massively Multiplayer Mayor in Cities XL (http://blog.wired.com/games/2008/08/cities-xl-mayor.html) 
 
 
---Quote--- 
You'll finally be able to take your fiscal skills and pit them against like-minded mayors in Cities XL, as the latest iteration of the City Life series for the PC...]]></description>
			<content:encoded><![CDATA[<div><a href="http://blog.wired.com/games/2008/08/cities-xl-mayor.html" target="_blank">Preview: Be a Massively Multiplayer Mayor in Cities XL</a><br />
<br />
<div style="margin:20px; margin-top:5px; ">
	<div class="smallfont" style="margin-bottom:2px">Quote:</div>
	<table cellpadding="6" cellspacing="0" border="0" width="100%">
	<tr>
		<td class="alt2">
			<hr />
			
				You'll finally be able to take your fiscal skills and pit them against like-minded mayors in Cities XL, as the latest iteration of the City Life series for the PC drifts into the realm of MMOs. <br />
<br />
I got a chance to look at an early build of Monte Cristo Games' city-builder title last week, and it looks to be shaping up quite nicely.<br />
<br />
The genre hasn't evolved much since Sim City established the basic rules: Plop down a few industrial, commercial and residential zones, sit around (or hit the fast-forward button) till they matriculate, collect taxes to buy a few roads, and zone more areas until you have the funds to keep the expansion process going. Eventually you'll establish a brimming metropolis, and maybe toss in a disaster or two to see how well your city-planning skills hold. <br />
<br />
City Life added social classes into the mix, each with their own particular needs and desires: The nouveau riche wouldn't be caught dead at a burger joint, while the average Joe or Jane could only afford to live in visually unappealing housing, and could only work at menial jobs in polluting industries. Toss in yuppies, hippies and other colorful civilian archetypes, and the aspiring mayor will find himself with a complex simulation game -- after all, you can't have a hospital unless you have high-income doctors to mend the patients, and low-income orderlies to mend the sheets.<br />
<br />
Cities XL hopes to perfect the stagnant city-builder genre, bringing the art of micromanagement to extremes. <br />
<br />
If serving as lord over a bunch of digital vassals is your thing, Cities XL attempts to grant you an unprecedented amount of control over every nook and cranny of your modern kingdom. Buildings can be zoned out in the traditional method, or you can select a particular structure by keyword (large, low-income residential only, for example) and plop individual structures down one by one. Zoom in a bit -- the camera goes from hovering at satellite level all the way down to a citizen's backyard -- and see people play soccer, sit in traffic or go about their workdays with the eerie feeling that they're being watched.   <br />
<br />
You can shape neighborhoods any way you please. If you're a fan of tidiness, you can use the traditional grid system, placing roads at right angles. Or you can leave your helpless populace to navigate a maddening, yet visually appealing, series of twists and turns. <br />
<br />
Add pedestrian-only thoroughfares to cut down on noise pollution in quiet neighborhoods, tack a few bus-only lanes onto your four-lane highway to convince people to use public transportation, establish bike paths to please those environmentally conscious hipsters who want to pedal to work ... and then juggle the nightmarish levels of traffic and disgruntled commuters who want nothing to do with the convoluted asphalt jungle you've constructed.<br />
<br />
To take things even further, Cities XL will offer expansion pack-esque Gameplay Extension Modules, or GEMs. The price of a GEM will vary based on the amount of gameplay it offers; the price range is tentatively set between $2 and $20. <br />
<br />
A Ski Resort GEM will come bundled with the game. It was the only one available during my test, but from what I saw, the levels of interaction are just this side of maddening. You'll be able to design a vacation resort from the ground up to complement your city, map out ski slopes with varying trail difficulties to sate the desires of novice and expert skiers, construct lifts and, of course, offer amenities and gift shops to help your patrons part with their hard-earned dollars. <br />
<br />
If you'd like to see how you're doing with your resort, just click on a patron and you'll get a dossier of their experience. You can find out what socioeconomic group they belong to, how much spending money they've brought along with them on their vacation (making adjustments to their quality of living back in the city as necessary), what they thought of a particular set of slopes (too difficult? Not as difficult as they'd like?), how many days they've been on vacation and how much money they spent on a particular day. <br />
<br />
Other GEMs might include a railroad GEM, giving you complete control over the rail industry you may have established in your town, or a winery GEM, which would allow you to create custom vintages ($400 bottles of cabernet or a $2 jug of Dr. Nate's Cure-All) to peddle to consumers and, potentially, other players.   <br />
<br />
We've all done the city-builder thing. Cities XL hopes to kick it up a notch by offering a massively multiplayer experience. With an optional fee of somewhere between $6 and $8 a month, you'll have access to Cities XL's subscription mode, called &quot;Planet offer,&quot; that will let you use your neurotic number-crunching and tax-balancing tendencies to compete or cooperate with like-minded mayors-in-training around the world. <br />
<br />
If you subscribe, you'll choose an Earth-like planet which will host thousands of players (think servers, in traditional MMO parlance) and scramble for a 10-kilometer-square plot of land on which to place one of your five allotted cities. Particular areas on a planet will provide specific resources, which will be crucial to your development: You can't build a ski resort in the middle of a desert, nor will you find much water, but you more than likely will have access to an abundance of oil. <br />
<br />
The game will then play as it does in the single-player mode, though you'll lack the ability to pause and control time. Fortunately, your city will progress at a much slower rate when you're logged out, so you won't return from a long break to find a smoldering ruin. The benefit of going online is, of course, all of the other folks to meet and greet. Players will be able to band together, establish city links by way of road, rail, air or sea, and trade cash and resources. <br />
<br />
The definition of a &quot;resource&quot; is a bit hazy, but in a good way. For example, you could potentially trade some of your excess oil to a city with a bountiful auto industry in exchange for getting your citizens access to vacations in that city's ski resorts, or a lowered price tag on imported vehicles. Cities can also work together, specializing in, and offering services, that benefit all: Natetopia pumps crude oil, Kohlerlandia refines it and Wiredville's sprawling transportation industry cuts both of our costs in distributing that gasoline to our own cities, and those who purchase from us.<br />
<br />
Social networking will be intertwined with the MMO experience. Those who participate in the Planet offer will be granted a player profile, listing all the stats and details of their cities, and any friends they may have made along the way. From the profile, you'll be able to  leave comments for others, write entries and post pictures in a journal (I had my first riot today!), or chat with other players and discuss business agendas and fiscal schemes, all from the comfort of your browser. <br />
<br />
At the Cities XL website, you'll also be able to shop for GEMs, new building models (if you'd like to take the customization even further) and topographic maps: buy a New York setting and you'll get a detailed replica of the city, so you can finally add the maximum security prison Central Park so desperately needs.  <br />
<br />
The game is still under development, with a tentative ship date of sometime in 2009. System requirements are up in the air at this point: I was told that the game would ideally be able to run on a 3-year-old system. But as anyone who's played a city-builder knows, once you've sculpted that complicated, sprawling empire, frame rates can drop into the single digits, even on beefy machines. We'll have to wait and see how that one plays out.
			
			<hr />
		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>
</div>Starpeace tried the exact same thing.</div>

